    %h2 Internet Anonymity with Tor and i2p
  %section
    %h3 What are Tor and i2p?
    %p
      %img{:src => '/images/presentations/tor.png', style: 'vertical-align: middle;'}
      %img{:src => '/images/presentations/itoopie.png', style: 'vertical-align: middle;'}
  %section
    %h3 What are Tor and i2p?
    %ul
      %li Tor is an anonymous internet proxy that allows users to use the Internet
      %li Invented at the Naval Research Lab, used by technologists, law enforcement, intelligence services, political activists, and more
      %li Tor also allows access to onion services, accessible only over Tor
      %li i2p, the Invisible Internet Project allows access to an alternative anonymous "Internet"
      %li Initially released in 2003, maintained mostly by pseudonymous developers
  %section
    %h3 How do Tor and i2p help?
    %ul
      %li Prevents a website or server from knowing your real IP address
      %li Prevents your ISP from watching what you do online
      %li But they do know that you're using Tor (without the use of bridges and the obfuscated pluggable transports) or i2p
      %li Internet anonymity promotes democracy, free speech and free thought by allowing users to research and express themselves without fear
  %section
    %h3 How do Tor and i2p work?
    %ul
      %li Tor uses "onion routing," multiple layers of encryption in a series of relays through a mix network
      %li By default, a client tunnels through 3 encrypted hops. Each node only knows the next and previous address
      %li A Tor node can be a middle relay, exit node, or onion service
      %li i2p uses "Garlic routing," as multiple packets can be encapsulated into a single i2p packet
  %section
    %h3 Differences between Tor and i2p
    %table
      %thead
        %tr.header
          %th Tor
          %th i2p
      %tbody
        %tr.odd
          %td Onion routing
          %td garlic routing
        %tr.even
          %td Proxy service
          %td private Internet
        %tr.odd
          %td Circuit switched
          %td packet switched
        %tr.even
          %td TCP only
          %td supports UDP
        %tr.odd
          %td Centralized services
          %td fully decentralized
        %tr.even
          %td USG funding
          %td anonymous volunteer developers
  %section
    %h3 Using Tor and i2p as a client
    %ul
      %li Tor Browser Bundle
      %li Avoid fingerprinting by blending in to the crowd
      %li Tor daemon and proxy configuration
      %li Useful for CLI tools and other software. See: torsocks(1), proxychains(1)
      %li Tails Live CD or USB that includes Tor and i2p (for now, v2.11)
      %li In-memory operating system, wiped on shutdown
  %section
    %h3 Running an Onion Service
    %ul
      %li An onion service allows a server to be accessible over a special .onion address
      %li Configure the HiddenServiceDir and HiddenServicePort directives in the torrc
      %li Security considerations
      %li Misconfigurations: disable server-status page
      %li Vulnerabilities: command injection, server exploits
      %li Timing attacks: don't run another service, don't run a relay
  %section
    %h3 Running a relay, exit node / router
    %ul
      %li If you'd like to support the Tor network, you can run a relay or exit node
      %li
        To run a Tor relay, configure your ORPort and ExitPolicy. For middle relay only,
        %code reject *:*
      %li If you run an exit node, you may get some strange traffic originating from your address
      %li You can filter most traffic that would attract attention by allowing only HTTPS (443)
      %li Alternatively, be prepared to explain what Tor is, or have a lawyer to do so
      %li Note: with i2p, you're a relay by default
  %section
