    %h2 Secure Instant Messaging with OTR and OMEMO
  %section
    %h3 What is OTR?
    %ul
      %li "Off The Record" messaging over instant messaging protocols like XMPP and AIM
      %li Extends IM with encryption, authentication, forward secrecy, and deniable authentication
      %li OTR supports file transfers (since version 3)
  %section
    %h3 How do I use OTR?
    %ul
      %li OTR can be installed as an extension to many popular instant messaging clients, such as Pidgin
      %li The Android app Xabber also supports OTR for secure instant messaging on the go
      %li Many clients can be configured to automatically initiate an OTR session
  %section
    %h3 How does OTR protect my communications?
    %ul
      %li Encrypts your communication from prying eyes
      %li Based on AES-128, Diffie-Hellman, and SHA-1
      %li Authenticates your communicating party
      %li Provides deniable encryption
  %section
    %h3 Where do I get OTR?
    %ul
      %li Available as a plugin for Pidgin (cross platform)
      %li Natively supported by
      %li Adium on OS X
      %li Kopete on UNIX-like systems
      %li Xabber and Conversations for Android
      %li ChatSecure for iOS
  %section
    %h3 What is OMEMO?
    %ul
      %li Next generation OTR with encrypted group chat support
      %li Introduced in Google Summer of Code 2015 to Conversations for Android
      %li Also offers forward secrecy and deniable encryption
  %section
    %h3 How is OMEMO different than OTR?
    %ul
      %li Supports group chat (multi-client end-to-end encryption)
      %li OMEMO uses the Double Ratchet algorithm (Signal)
  %section
    %h3 Where can I get OMEMO?
    %ul
      %li Originally written for Conversations for Android
      %li ChatSecure for iOS supports OMEMO
      %li Cross-platform client Gajim supports OMEMO through a plugin
  %section
    %h3 Bonus: Anonymous, encrypted messaging with Ricochet
    %ul
      %li Dedicated, Tor-based instant messenger
      %li Use Tor onion addresses instead of usernames or nick names
      %li End-to-end message encryption
      %li No central servers or middle man
      %li Eliminates conversation metadata
      %li Soon to support file transfers (or use OnionShare)










