  %section
    %h2 Quantum Cryptography
  %section
    %h3 Quantum changes everything
    %ul
      %li Quantum breaks common cryptography
      %li Quantum enables new better cryptography
  %section
    %p There are two types of traditional cryptography
    %ul
      %li Symmetric
      %li Asymmetric
  %section
    %h3 Symmetric
    %ul
      %li Encrypt and decrypt keys are the same
      %li Key exchange is hard
      %li Typically very fast
      %li Used for encrypting data
  %section
    %h3 Asymmetric
    %ul
      %li Encrypt and decrypt keys are different
      %li Typically very slow
      %li Mostly used for encrypting symmetric encryption keys
  %section
    %h3 Common Asymmetric Encryption
    %ul
      %li
        %em RSA
      %li Depends on the assumption that factoring a product of two very large prime numbers is hard
      %li
        %em Diffie–Hellman/ElGamal
      %li Depends on the assumption that the discrete log problem is hard
  %section
    %h3 Quantum computing breaks common cryptography
    %ul
      %li
        %em Shor's algorithm
      %li Uses a quantum computer to efficiently factor very large numbers
      %li Also works for discrete logs
      %li Symmetric is thought to be mostly safe
  %section
    %h3 Quantum enables new better cryptography
    %ul
      %li
        Quantum mechanics provide useful guarantees
      %li It is impossible to copy data encoded in a quantum state
      %li The very act of reading data encoded in a quantum state changes the state










